                            <comment id="16291843" author="paulk" created="Fri, 15 Dec 2017 00:35:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll have to look at the code and tests to remember for sure but I think there is some provision made for Map-based properties, i.e. this is allowed:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
@Immutable
&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;class &lt;/span&gt;Point {
  TreeMap props
}

TreeMap map = [color: &lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;red&apos;&lt;/span&gt;, x: 2, y: -3]
println &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; Point(map)
println &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; Point(props: map)
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So both an ordered tuple constructor (with TreeMap arg) and map-based constructor (with HashMap arg) are provided.&lt;br/&gt;
There are issues if props above is made a Map or HashMap for example and I think only one Map-based constructor is provided. Perhaps the assumptions behind that code can be improved though.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16388722" author="paulk" created="Tue, 6 Mar 2018 23:38:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This was fixed as part of recent changes for 2.5.0-beta-3 but I forgot to close this issue before release. Commit: e5e8fe1af3&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It means in your example you can now do:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
def p3 = &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; Point(&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; TreeMap(coordinates))
&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;assert&lt;/span&gt; p3.x == 1
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
